    <Entry>
      <ID>1</ID>
      <DefaultText>Blue. Once, you had two dozen words for all its hues and shades; metaphors to glaives' capes and courtesans' eyes. Now, the sky is just... blue. The ground is stone. The man before you, fat. Now, all is vague and drab, like...{VOICE: : At "like..." the narrator (or anyway the POV MPC) is groping for a metaphor and can't find one.}
 
The Memorialist sees you've stopped, and he halts as well. "Let's have a rest, then," he says, passing you a bottle of fortified water as he catches his breath. You knew a word for that, too, this drink they brew in the Valley of Dead Heroes. Gone. "We aren't far from his cenotaph." The fat man wipes his brow. {VOICE: "Gone" should be a powerful blow with a longer than usual pause after the period.}

Deep in your pocket, your hand feels for the round tin that holds the worms; your fingers clutch it tight and as they do, they brush a piece of paper. {VOICE: "The worms" should be delivered ominously, faintly disgustedly. The worms are the MPC's addiction; he craves and loathes them}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>2</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Are you his shadow?" the Memorialist asks abruptly. "Kalaghat Anvor, I mean. The one you came to see."

Without waiting for a response, he barrels onward. "We thought he'd cast his shadows among his own kind. We reasoned that with the Tabaht gone, his line was lost forever."

He stops and flushes more deeply, then, hastily, with a sign, adds, "But shadows fall where they will, as they will." {VOICE: "But shadows fall . . . as they will." This is a kind of catechism-type line, delivered by rote and note entirely believingly. Note that line has a deliberate staccato structure designed to run slightly at odds with the "hastily" - it emphasizes how the Memorialist is a bit thrown off, nervous, jangled.}

Kalaghat Anvor. Tabaht. Shadows. They flit around the edges of your mind, escaping your grasp. But the worms... they are well within reach. {VOICE: Now when the narrator says "worms" the disgust is largely gone: I hear this almost a little huskily, anticipating their pleasure. However, the "they are well within reach" could have a more ominous sound.}

"Shall we continue, pilgrim?" the Memorialist asks, to break the silence. "One more short hike will do it."

Your body is ready. Your mind is not. {VOICE: Similarly, I would add some dread to "your mind is not."}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
