    <Entry>
      <ID>11</ID>
      <DefaultText>You slip the crisp, neatly folded sheet from your pocket and carefully open it.

"I will want the worms, but I will be strong. I will wonder what I have lost, but they will only rob me further. I will endure, and I will build the tower of my intellect anew. Kalaghat Anvor will furnish the material. The Mindlink, not the worms, will be my tool."

The Mindlink.

A dead-eyed trader from Haref sold it for the last of your once-great heap of prizes and bounties. Now it's slung from your belt, a hideous mask with a synth tube hanging off it like some sathoshi tentacle.

{[B] SOUND: Paper sliding and then being unfolded.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>12</ID>
      <DefaultText>The trembling form of the letters tells more The trembling strokes that poorly form each letter tell more than the rote promises of strength and endurance. It is a letter that has been written many times, and in the end tossed aside.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>13</ID>
      <DefaultText>The tin is old and unremarkable: scuffed and dented but sturdy enough. It opens easily.

Inside is a clump of bristly worms, blind and thin, barely moving. Your fingers itch and tremble. Your nostrils flare. You no longer know their name, but you know exactly how to use them.

Careful not to spill the precious contents, you close the tin and slide it back into your pocket.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>14</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Each of us is a shadow of a great one interred beneath this ground. The only way to understand the light that shines behind this world of darkness is for the shadow to stand beside the hero who cast it, by each staring at the other, to learn of the light we cannot see."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>15</ID>
      <DefaultText>REMOVE HIGH

What a walk.  Arrive at Cenotaph.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>16</ID>
      <DefaultText>The Memorialist regards you skeptically, as if he expects to be the butt of a joke. As he looks in your eyes, however, he softens.

"We live in a world of darkness, pilgrim, and each of us is just a shadow of one of the great heroes buried here in this valley. But there's a light that shines behind the world. To know it, we shadows must measure ourselves against the heroes who cast us, and thus learn the light that lives beyond."

He takes a swig from the canteen. "I thought you set out on this pilgrimage to visit the tomb of Kalaghat Anvor because you were his shadow. That you wanted to stand before him and find enlightenment. Am I wrong? Are you his shadow or not?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>17</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Yes, I'm his shadow."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>18</ID>
      <DefaultText>"No, I'm not."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>19</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I don't know."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>20</ID>
      <DefaultText>The memorialist nods. "That's how it is. I've met pilgrims who swore they were lords and ladies of old, but when they reached the grave, wept in shame. But I've also seen a novice stumble across her hero by mere chance. If you find Kalaghat Anvor, you will know who you are, or are not."

He gestures to the hilltop toward which you've been hiking. "Just over that rise is the monument. As for his tomb... you said that the cenotaph would lead the way. I can't see how, but for the famous puzzle-breaker of Sagus Cliffs, I'm sure it will be simple."

Your mind might still be clouded, but at least now the form of things has become clearer.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>21</ID>
      <DefaultText>The man looks crestfallen at your answer, but in the end he shrugs. "Pilgrims cross the valley for reasons of their own - to mourn, to gawk. It's not my place to judge."

He gestures to the hilltop toward which you've been hiking. "Just over that rise is the monument. As for his tomb... you said that the cenotaph would lead the way. I can't see how, but for the famous puzzle-breaker of Sagus Cliffs, I'm sure it will be simple."

Your mind might still be clouded, but at least now the form of things has become clearer.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>22</ID>
      <DefaultText>The memorialist smiles. "It's a rare honor to join shadow and hero, and a joy for those of us who shepherd pilgrims through the valley."

He gestures to the hilltop toward which you've been hiking. "Just over that rise is the monument. As for his tomb... you said that the cenotaph would lead the way. I can't see how, but for the famous puzzle-breaker of Sagus Cliffs, I'm sure it will be simple."

Your mind might still be clouded, but at least now the form of things has become clearer.</DefaultText>
