      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>39</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you follow the Memorialist up the crumbling path, he carries on about a time when all the roads in the valley were as well-paved as the streets of Sagus Cliffs. Then, reaching the hillcrest, he falls into reverential silence.

When you catch up, you see the sight that awed him even for the thousandth time: a clutch of exquisite monuments, ranging from vast to miniature, from abstract to eerily lifelike. The Memorialist points to one of them - a many-sided slab of black stone - and gestures for you to follow.

This must be the cenotaph of Kalaghat Anvor, Tabaht general and would-be world conqueror.

{[B] SOUND: Walking up a rocky path.}

{IMAGE 2: The Cenotaph}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>40</ID>
      <DefaultText>Up close, the cenotaph is not so remarkable. Its faces are adorned with gruesome, stylized reliefs depicting the Tabaht and their dragolith mounts trampling the corpses of their foes. Neat, geometric glyphs encircle the panels. Like the images themselves, they are embossed rather than engraved.

The Memorialist clears his throat. "Of course, Kalaghat Anvor isn't *here*. Like the other heroes, his body's in one of the cells in the catacombs beneath us." He nods at the monument. "This is its own sort of shadow - all memorials are."

As your guide mumbles something about the difference between expression, impression, and reality, your attention returns to the cenotaph itself.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
