    <Entry>
      <ID>77</ID>
      <DefaultText>You step toward the wavering energy field and stare at the blue-tinged tomb beyond. The blood price has been paid, and Kalaghat Anvor rests within.

Tarrying no longer, you plunge through.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>78</ID>
      <DefaultText>Horrible death!</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>80</ID>
      <DefaultText>You step toward the wavering energy field and stare at the blue-tinged tomb beyond. The resting place of Kalaghat Anvor.

The Memorialist remains at a respectful distance.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>81</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>82</ID>
      <DefaultText> "May you find enlightenment beside your hero, pilgrim."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>83</ID>
      <DefaultText> "Whatever it is you seek, pilgrim, I hope you find it within."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>84</ID>
      <DefaultText> "I will pray that your hero awaits within, pilgrim, and that you find enlightenment at his side."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>85</ID>
      <DefaultText>The tomb's walls are bare stone, as is its floor. In fact, the room is empty except for the sarcophagus that sits at its center, a crystalline numenera that hums with ancient, indefatigable energy. Bathed in the portal's light, the room feels almost underwater, a sensation heightened by the air's unnatural weight.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>93</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>94</ID>
      <DefaultText>War. Blood. Battle. Death. Those symbols are graven in your mind just as they are on the cenotaph. But you can squeeze no more meaning from memory than you can from the stone.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>95</ID>
      <DefaultText>What seemed at first individual glyphs are far more complex: smaller symbols assembled into larger patterns, linked into chains, twined and twisted into knots. Never a tangle or ramble: it is more mathematical or scientific notation than language.

Running your fingers across the glyphs, you see that they shine briefly under your touch, then fade.

Perhaps there is a formula here to be solved, a structure, a higher, hidden order to be found. Perhaps here you could catch glimmers of the Tabaht's military mastery. But the sieve of your mind holds nothing, and any secrets slip right through.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>96</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you struggle to decipher the symbols, the Memorialist hurries over. "This one means 'war,'" he says, illuminating a cluster repeated endlessly on the cenotaph. "This one, 'death.'"

He picks out others and shows how the ideogram for "soldier" weaves into "warband," which can in turn mesh into "column" or "army."

Excitement grows in his voice as he leads you to another panel and shows you the unique markings that compose the pattern for "Underspine." "A high council, we think, or god."

He notes what seems to be a structure to the writing - a pattern within the pattern. "Could it be a puzzle to open the way to Kalaghat Anvor?" he asks, expectantly.

You have no answer for his hopes.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>97</ID>
      <DefaultText>In the end, they mean no more to you than the scratches on the wall of an empty cell. Someone was here, and now is gone.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>102</ID>
      <DefaultText>Now you know the symbol wrapped around the basin's lip. "Blood." Of course. It could be nothing else.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>103</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>104</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>105</ID>
      <DefaultText>Sacrifice the Memorialist.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>106</ID>
      <DefaultText>Spill some of your blood in the basin.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>107</ID>
      <DefaultText>Beneath your guide's worried gaze, you nick your wrist and drizzle some blood into the bowl. Nothing comes of it. Whatever flows through your veins will not slake the stone's thirst.

{[B] SOUND: A cutting noise and then a few drips of blood.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>108</ID>
      <DefaultText>Perhaps your guide underestimates the strength still coiled in your sinews; perhaps he imagines your body has gone soft as your mind. Or maybe his faith gives him no cause to fear leaving this world of shadows.

Whatever the case, he hardly seems to flinch as you swing a jagged rock toward his head. The sound is more a thud than a crack, but any fool could see his skull is smashed.

You drag his body to the basin and saw at his neck until the blood begins to run, filling the bowl faster than its narrow drain can empty.

You step back and watch as the glyphs glow bright blue, casting with their light a kind of shimmering portal in the air. Through it, you see hints of a room.

{[A] SOUND: Rock hitting a skull, followed by someone falling.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>109</ID>
      <DefaultText>The tin is old and unremarkable: scuffed and dented but sturdy enough. It opens easily.

Inside is a mound of worm-like grubs, blind and thin, barely moving. You fingers itch and tremble. Your nostrils flare. You no longer know their name, but you know exactly how to use them.

Careful not to spill the precious contents, you close the tin and slide it back into your pocket.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
