    <Entry>
      <ID>114</ID>
      <DefaultText>Try to find the correct sequence of glyphs.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>115</ID>
      <DefaultText>Your fingers race across the glyphs, which now do not fade as you progress. Rather, with each touch they grow brighter and brighter.

You can hear the excited gasp from your guide as you reach the last side of the cenotaph. With a flourish, you press the final symbols. The skein ends in "war," of course.

Blue light pours forth from the cenotaph, forming a kind of shimmering portal. Through it, you see hints of a room. "His tomb," whispers the Memorialist.

A smile sneaks onto your face as you see the way before you.

{[A] SOUND: "Sound" of techno-magic lights turning on.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>116</ID>
      <DefaultText>You trick yourself into thinking that you can crack whatever code the stone holds, but neither logic nor luck makes any headway.

The glyphs shine and fade, but nothing happens. Given the endless combinations, not even the persistence you had of old could break through this lock.

{[A] SOUND: "Sound" of techno-magic lights turning on.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>117</ID>
      <DefaultText>Once again, you guess at possible series of glyphs that might provoke some reaction from the cenotaph. If there is a key, you do not find it.

{[A] SOUND: "Sound" of techno-magic lights turning on.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>119</ID>
      <DefaultText>Open the sarcophagus.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>120</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>121</ID>
      <DefaultText>A few twists of the coffin's cylindrical locks, and the lid rises up with a hiss of icy, age-old air. As the mist clears, you see at last the face of Kalaghat Anvor.

You feel nothing at the sight of him, never having known the terror of his triumvirate. His inhuman features are slightly mummified, but well preserved; his ebon tabard is faded with time that even the sarcophagus could not keep at bay.

But it is his head that matters, not his clothes. His head, and its brain, and the insight sheathed within, an edge keen enough to cut through the tangle of your own failures.

{[A] SOUND: Hissing sound of a hermetically sealed coffin opening.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>122</ID>
      <DefaultText>Use the Mindlink on the Tabaht corpse.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>123</ID>
      <DefaultText>Once you slip the helmet over your face, you can't see and can barely breathe. Trapped in the mask's damp darkness, you fumble for the socket at the base of the corpse's skull. At last you find it, and - still struggling - try to bring the conduit tube into contact.

Suddenly, the darkness explodes with light: the nebulous, patchwork glow of your own mind and, beyond it, the glorious mandala formed by the thoughts of Kalaghat Anvor.

A mote emerges from that pattern, and a confused voice whispers, "You are not the Underspine."

Almost instantly, the geometry of his mind transforms into a star fortress from whose bastions dagger-like shapes stream forth. {[A] SOUND: Heavy breathing in a mask.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>126</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>127</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>128</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You will not taint my thoughts," the Tabaht voice rumbles as his fleet soars toward you. There's no time to try and reason with him, if that would ever be possible.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>129</ID>
      <DefaultText>Fend him off. You came here to rebuild your mind, not to offer it up for Tabaht pillaging.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>130</ID>
      <DefaultText>Let him in. You came here to fill the vast gaps in your mind, and perhaps this would be the swiftest way.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>131</ID>
      <DefaultText>Mount your own attack. You came here to hone your mind, and perhaps this is the way to do so.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>132</ID>
      <DefaultText>Death has not dulled the Tabaht's weapons or his will. But the mind is more than a mere battlefield, and riddled and rotten as yours may be, it is not yet bereft of all its old gifts.

You confound Anvor's vanguard with a flurry of bright weavings, while stabbing your own lines of thought deep into the perfect geometry of his mind. In the end, that is all it takes: his thoughts destroy themselves, unraveling even as they seek to mend the breaches you have cut. Bit by bit, order turns to chaos, and the great light of Kalaghat Anvor to a mere shadow.

As he fades, you slip free of the Mindlink, and - moments later - of the Tabaht's tomb.

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of sound for minds battling: they're kind of shooting out energy at each other, or parts of thoughts. I'm at a loss to what sounds should be, but I think we do need some sound here. Maybe almost TRONish?}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>133</ID>
      <DefaultText>Whatever weapons your mind once wielded have long since been worn blunt by the worms, and what remains cannot by any means match the will of Kalaghat Anvor.

He knocks aside your sally and then, with wild violence, hacks apart your memories and fears, doubts and despair, tattering the fabric of your self. You watch helplessly, and with failing comprehension, as blue-black blotches spread across your mind.

In the end, it all means nothing to the masked fool crouched beside a corpse, drooling, moaning, and weeping without knowing why.

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of sound for minds battling: they're kind of shooting out energy at each other, or parts of thoughts. I'm at a loss to what sounds should be, but I think we do need some sound here. Maybe almost TRONish?}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>137</ID>
      <DefaultText>You knit shut the ragged fringes of your mind, focusing and contracting yourself into a tight, hard core bound by its will to live.

The cutting thoughts of Kalaghat Anvor flash at the perimeter of your defenses, probing, testing, seeking entry, but to no avail.

At length they withdraw to the Tabaht's own pattern. For now, you are safe.

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of sound for minds battling: they're kind of shooting out energy at each other, or parts of thoughts. I'm at a loss to what sounds should be, but I think we do need some sound here. Maybe almost TRONish?}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>138</ID>
      <DefaultText>You try to knit shut the ragged fringes of your worm-eaten mind and mount some defense, but Kalaghat Anvor quickly overwhelms you.

With wild violence, his sharp-edged thoughts hack through your memories and fears, doubts and despair, tattering the fabric of your self. You watch helplessly, and with failing comprehension, as blue-black blotches spread across your mind. Too long have you traded the substance of your strength for the worms' flashes of brilliance, and now you've nothing left to stem this rout.

In the end, it all means nothing to the masked fool crouched beside a corpse, drooling, moaning, and weeping without knowing why.

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of sound for minds battling: they're kind of shooting out energy at each other, or parts of thoughts. I'm at a loss to what sounds should be, but I think we do need some sound here. Maybe almost TRONish?}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>139</ID>
      <DefaultText>The vanguard of the general's mind pierces into your own and sweeps across it, surveying the landscape and its defenders before withdrawing to the neutral darkness between you. You can see the Tabaht's disgust in the shape and color of his thoughts.

{[B] SOUND: Variant on the mind-battle. If we can't get to this sound, use the mind battle sound.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>140</ID>
      <DefaultText>As the vanguard of the general's mind pierces into your own, a sense of revulsion overwhelms you: not your own disgust, but that of Kalaghat Anvor at the rotten husk left by the mnemotodes.

"No!" he roars. "Your trap will not take me!"

His thoughts flee from your mind, and seem to curl in upon themselves in a flurry of self-destruction. Moments later, there is nothing but darkness, and you have no choice but to draw the Mindlink from your head.

{[B] SOUND: Variant on the mind battle sound. See note 139.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>141</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>142</ID>
      <DefaultText>

It seems madness that he fears you could pollute his mind, when merely fending off his force shall be at the limits of your worm-wasted will.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>143</ID>
      <DefaultText>

Against such force of will, you fear your worm-eaten mind can mount no meaningful fight.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>147</ID>
      <DefaultText>The texture of the general's mind ripples as he arranges his thoughts, absorbs what his scouts have scraped from your mind. At last, like a messenger, a sphere splits off from the pattern and floats before you.

"Pilgrim." The word is spat out. "I have seen the secrets you keep from yourself: the Endless Battle you meant to end, and the red wreckage your *solution* left behind. I am unmoved. I killed more, lost more, and fell farther without surrendering the truth."

The sphere shimmers and flattens into a kind of mirror. "You have come because you would prove yourself again. Through me. By me."

The thought floats slowly backward. "But I am not your Underspine."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>148</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>149</ID>
      <DefaultText>Attack his mind and plunder his knowledge.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>150</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>151</ID>
      <DefaultText>Attempt to break the Mindlink.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>152</ID>
      <DefaultText>Study the sarcophagus.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>153</ID>
      <DefaultText>The sarcophagus is divided into three parts: a wide bier, an elongated pentagonal coffin, and a curved, lens-like lid.

The bier is decorated with familiar glyphs: you recognize "war" and "death" and "purity" among them. But these designs hold little interest: they are just catchwords, and they will teach you nothing of the Tabaht genius.

The coffin, for its part, is a single hunk of milky aquamarine. Its lid is less opaque, and through it you can see the corpse's silhouette. Most importantly, you notice a simple locking mechanism holding the two together; opening the sarcophagus would be a straightforward matter.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>154</ID>
      <DefaultText>The sarcophagus is divided into three parts: a wide bier, an elongated pentagonal coffin, and a curved, lens-like lid.

The bier is decorated with meaningless geometric glyphs that hold little interest.

The coffin, for its part, is a single hunk of milky aquamarine. Its lid is less opaque, and through it you can see the corpse's silhouette. Most importantly, you notice a simple locking mechanism holding the two together: opening the sarcophagus would be a straightforward matter.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>155</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>156</ID>
      <DefaultText>Study his mind.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>157</ID>
      <DefaultText>Study his mind again.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>158</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>159</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>160</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>161</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>162</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>163</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I want to learn the trick of Tabaht warfare."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>164</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Tell me more about your philosophy."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>165</ID>
      <DefaultText>A purple ripple runs across the mind of Kalaghat Anvor, and you feel the harsh rasp of Tabaht laughter.

"The weak-willed and degenerate always dream that the great prevail by 'tricks' or cheats or chance." His thoughts array themselves in interlinked chains of blue and black. "But war disabuses tricksters of their vanity. Failure falls upon those proved false by battle, and victory is the stamp of truth."

The chains stretch and run throughout the patterns of his mind. "We did not master deceit or even war; we mastered our own authentic selves. We triumphed by philosophy, not strategy."

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of warping/transforming sound, though remember we're in imaginary space, we're talking about like an energy field changing.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>166</ID>
      <DefaultText>A small cube of ideas detaches from the pattern of the general's mind and unfolds before you.

"In all systems, the variable is subordinate to the constant. The measure of things must be fixed." Lines of thought stab out from the unfolded eidolon, probing your mind like outriders. "You do not comprehend."

The eidolon rearranges itself into a pyramid. "When one stands at the utmost peak of the highest mountain, an advance is no better than a retreat: all change is decline." Again he probes, and again you are found wanting.

"To not fall, one must say, 'There is no more ascent. Here I stay.' Many have so spoken, but the Tabaht alone spoke truly, resisting the vanity of progress."

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of warping/transforming sound, though remember we're in imaginary space, we're talking about like an energy field changing.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>167</ID>
      <DefaultText>Given the sudden jagged configuration of his mind, Anvor seems affronted by your question. At last, he sends forth a sphere in answer.

"The conqueror's sword flexes, but always straightens to its proper form." The sphere shimmers and turns golden. "All great peoples have found mighty truths, but always they let their truths mingle with falsehood and frivolity until their folkways become fractious, friable. We alone held to our truth with unflinching conviction."

The sphere stretches into a toroid. "Words. Faith. Art. All was held pure and unchanging within the Underspine - a perfect, eternal purpose spanning all generations. What can stand before such united trust?"

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of warping/transforming sound, though remember we're in imaginary space, we're talking about like an energy field changing.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>168</ID>
      <DefaultText>Dark wedges wheel themselves into a wall, shielding the inner citadel of the general's mind.

"You are not fit to know more of our thoughts: you would warp them in your twisted vessel, or else your mind would burst in trying to contain them."

There is no way to pierce the barrier he has raised, and it is clear his mind will not be changed.

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of warping/transforming sound, though remember we're in imaginary space, we're talking about like an energy field changing.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>171</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>172</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I want you to fill the emptiness in my mind."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>173</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I'll ask you again: join me."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>174</ID>
      <DefaultText>Death has not dulled the Tabaht's weapons or his will. But the mind is more than a mere battlefield, and riddled and rotten as yours may be, it is not yet bereft of all its old gifts.

You confound Anvor's defenses with a flurry of bright weavings, while stabbing your lines of thought deep into the perfect geometry of his mind. In the end, that is all it takes: his thoughts destroy themselves, unraveling even as they seek to mend the breaches you have cut. Order turns to chaos, and the great light of Kalaghat Anvor to a mere shadow.

In this rout, you rip whatever wisdom you want from his supine mind. Then, as he fades, you slip free of the Mindlink, and - moments later - of the Tabaht's tomb.

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of sound for minds battling: they're kind of shooting out energy at each other, or parts of thoughts. I'm at a loss to what sounds should be, but I think we do need some sound here. Maybe almost TRONish?}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>175</ID>
      <DefaultText>Death has not dulled the Tabaht's weapons or his will, and he has used the time in the Mindlink to gather his forces. And your mind, for all your bold gambit, languishes in worm-worn decline.

With wild violence, his sharp-edged thoughts hack through your memories and fears, doubts and despair, tattering the fabric of your self. You watch helplessly, and with failing comprehension, as blue-black blotches spread across your mind. Too long have you traded the substance of your strength for the worms' flashes of brilliance, and now you've nothing left to stem this rout.

In the end, it all means nothing to the masked fool crouched beside a corpse, drooling, moaning, and weeping without knowing why.

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of sound for minds battling: they're kind of shooting out energy at each other, or parts of thoughts. I'm at a loss to what sounds should be, but I think we do need some sound here. Maybe almost TRONish?}
</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>176</ID>
      <DefaultText>The texture of the general's mind ripples as he arranges his thoughts, absorbs what his scouts have scraped from your mind. At last, like a messenger, a sphere splits off from the pattern and floats before you.

"Pilgrim." The word is spat out. "I have seen the secrets you keep from yourself: the Endless Battle you meant to end, and the red wreckage your *solution* left behind. I am unmoved. I killed more, lost more, and fell farther without surrendering the truth."

The sphere shimmers and flattens into a kind of mirror. "You have come because you would prove yourself again. Through me. By me."

The thought floats slowly backward. "But I am not your Underspine."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>177</ID>
      <DefaultText>The texture of the general's mind ripples as he arranges his thoughts, absorbs what his scouts have scraped from your mind. At last, like a messenger, a sphere splits off from the pattern and floats before you.

"Pilgrim." The word is spat out. "I have seen the secrets you keep from yourself: the Endless Battle you meant to end, and the red wreckage your *solution* left behind. I am unmoved. I killed more, lost more, and fell farther without surrendering the truth."

The sphere shimmers and flattens into a kind of mirror. "You have come because you would prove yourself again. Through me. By me."

The thought floats slowly backward. "But I am not your Underspine."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>178</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>179</ID>
      <DefaultText> It is a vast force, enough to encircle your own mind completely.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>180</ID>
      <DefaultText> Their ranks are growing.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>181</ID>
      <DefaultText> At the moment, they are scattered and in some disarray.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>182</ID>
      <DefaultText>More battles, bloodshed, and butchery flash before you.

In the depths of the general's mind, jagged, violent thoughts seem to be mustering as if for war.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>183</ID>
      <DefaultText>You see a city, underground, the tunnel walls and vaulting chambers adorned with carvings of fallen enemies.

You see battles, endless battles, the memories sorted with meticulous care, conjoined by formations employed, foes faced, weapons wielded, terrain accommodated. It seems a catalogue without end.

In the depths of the general's mind, jagged, violent thoughts seem to be mustering as if for war.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>184</ID>
      <DefaultText>You see a wide crescent of uraeyl reavers, ready to sweep down on an outnumbered but unfazed band of Tabaht scouts. You know they will fight free because Anvor knew it then, before the battle even began.

You see the city of Sagus Cliffs, rising above the plains like a beacon, a treasure, a false icon to be smashed to pieces.

In the depths of the general's mind, jagged, violent thoughts seem to be mustering as if for war.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>185</ID>
      <DefaultText>Death has not dulled the Tabaht's weapons or his will. But the mind is more than a mere battlefield, and riddled and rotten as yours may be, it is not yet bereft of all its old gifts.

Lines of thought race between you, and great jagged rifts are torn in the fabric of your minds. Defenses tighten, feints fly, and wills pound against each other in brute desire.

Plainly, there can be no end to this but the destruction of you both.

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of sound for minds battling: they're kind of shooting out energy at each other, or parts of thoughts. I'm at a loss to what sounds should be, but I think we do need some sound here. Maybe almost TRONish?}
</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>186</ID>
      <DefaultText>"We're well matched. Join minds with me."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>187</ID>
      <DefaultText>Break the Mindlink.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>188</ID>
      <DefaultText>With wild violence, his sharp-edged thoughts hack through your memories and fears, doubts and despair, tattering the fabric of your self. You watch helpless, and with failing comprehension, as blue-black blotches spread across your mind. 

In the end, it all means nothing to the masked fool crouched beside a corpse, drooling, moaning, and weeping without knowing why.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>189</ID>
      <DefaultText>Anvor strives to bind you, to encircle and ensnare your thoughts for a final, fatal battle. But your mind is supple and long ago learned to slip free from where it would not dwell.

The darkness between you grows, the light of his pattern dims, and soon you are once more wrapped in a reeking leather mask. 

You pull the Mindlink off and, without a backward glance for the Tabaht corpse, stagger forth from the tomb.

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of sound for minds battling: they're kind of shooting out energy at each other, or parts of thoughts. I'm at a loss to what sounds should be, but I think we do need some sound here. Maybe almost TRONish?}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>190</ID>
      <DefaultText>The blue portal fades behind you; the blue sky spreads above. A breeze blows across your sweat-soaked skin. Monuments stretch as far as the eye can see: shadows, the Memorialist called them.

Your mind has shadows of its own, some blackened by Anvor, some by the worms, and some by older, darker causes. But for now, the sun shines down upon you and you have left death in the tomb. {[A] SOUND: Outdoors-y sounds: wind blowing, maybe birds chirping.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>191</ID>
      <DefaultText>Ending 2.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>192</ID>
      <DefaultText>Ending 3.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>193</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Your kind has been wiped out."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>194</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you tell the Tabaht general of his kind's demise, the geometric perfection of his thoughts fractures for a moment - not quite into chaos or organic shapes, but into sharp shards that cannot quite reform. Some of these needles jab into your own mind, probing, confirming that you tell the truth.

"I see," Anvor answers.

Eventually, the fragments of his mind reform, though the ranks of its guardians seem thinned. "At least they are safe from the corruption of change. To be frozen forever in cold death is a better fate than the seamy, teeming welter of your city."

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of warping/transforming sound, though remember we're in imaginary space, we're talking about like an energy field changing.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>196</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>197</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Tell me more about your philosophy."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>198</ID>
      <DefaultText>Examine the images.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>200</ID>
      <DefaultText>No doubt some historian could tell the tale behind each panel - what doomed race the Tabaht annihilated here, what grand battle was waged there - but to you they're just an ugly blur that tugs at shameful memories without ever quite dragging them to the surface. This is not the knowledge you came for.

On one side of the cenotaph, there's something else: an obscene picture, crudely etched rather than raised, its edges scorched black. The Memorialist clears his throat awkwardly. "A graffito from just after the Tabaht were beaten, carved with a plasma torch by a bitter nano."

He coughs again. "The, ah, visual pun on 'Black Three' must be obvious. Sadly, we can't possibly fix the damage."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>201</ID>
      <DefaultText>

Tarrying no longer, you plunge through.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>202</ID>
      <DefaultText>Examine the portal.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>203</ID>
      <DefaultText>Some sort of room, bathed in blue light, lies beyond the portal. The tomb of Kalaghat Anvor, it would seem.

The knowledge you seek awaits within.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>204</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>205</ID>
      <DefaultText>Study the basin.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>206</ID>
      <DefaultText>Look at the basin again.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>207</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>208</ID>
      <DefaultText>Neither the smooth, simple form of the basin nor its geometric fringe reveals any new secrets.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>209</ID>
      <DefaultText>Carved into the cenotaph's plinth in a wide, shallow bowl, perfectly smooth, perfectly ovoid. In its center is a small drain that runs into the monument. Around its rim is a geometric pattern, simple and composed of a single recurrent shape.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>210</ID>
      <DefaultText>You recognize the symbol: "Blood." Of course. What else could it be?</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>211</ID>
      <DefaultText>

Your guide keeps back from the basin as you examine it, and shares no thoughts.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>212</ID>
      <DefaultText>"What is the Underspine?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>213</ID>
      <DefaultText>Kalaghat Anvor's mind grows still, with faint flashes of contemplation flickering across its surface.

"The guardian of the Tabaht soul." His mind darkens and storms. "To use your words befouls the meaning of my thoughts. It is obscene that you call this tongue 'Truth.'"

Silence. Then: "The Underspine is a filter through which our minds flow, cleansing us of distraction, subversion, novelty, and doubt."

The darkness dances to the edges of his will. "You cannot comprehend."

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of warping/transforming sound, though remember we're in imaginary space, we're talking about like an energy field changing.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>214</ID>
      <DefaultText>The sky outside is still blue: blue and vast and unbound. It needs no words to hem it in. Like the pilgrim beneath it, it is fertile in its emptiness, not barren.

With empty pockets and a yearning mind, you return to a journey that is not only unfinished, but barely begun. {[A] SOUND: Outdoors-y sounds: wind blowing, maybe birds chirping.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>215</ID>
      <DefaultText>"What did you see in me?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>216</ID>
      <DefaultText>His mind ripples with amusement. "Fear. Vanity. Weakness. Deceit." There is a long silence. "It is your duty to know yourself, and to be yourself."

A thin, silver sliver of thought shoots out from his mind and stabs into your own. It is an image: a battlefield, strewn with countless corpses and shattered war-machines. A regal woman stands beside you, rigid with rage. "Puzzle-breaker, indeed," she sneers.

The image - be it memory or Tabaht deception - fades away, and Kalaghat Anvor offers no more.

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of warping/transforming sound, though remember we're in imaginary space, we're talking about like an energy field changing.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>217</ID>
      <DefaultText>Bright flashes race through the pathways of his mind as it forms and reforms in myriad shapes and patterns. At last, a single word: "Yes."

The pattern breaks, and its fragments, jagged and disjointed, ricochet across the darkness, crashing into your mind. You feel the terror that has gripped him, the fierce imperative to stand against the outright obliteration of his race, whatever the price. You sense the contempt in which he holds you, mingled with a grudging knowledge that there will come no better chance.

And then there is no more "you" and no more "Anvor", only a madcap image assembled from two puzzles jumbled together, only that and the darkness beyond.

{[B] SOUND: Some kind of "merging" sound. We can use the "warping" sound if we don't get to this.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>218</ID>
      <DefaultText>The general's mind darkens; its defenses harden. "Conquest holds its own doom. The risk is too great."

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of warping/transforming sound, though remember we're in imaginary space, we're talking about like an energy field changing.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>219</ID>
      <DefaultText>A row of red-rimmed pyramids sprouts along the fringe of Anvor's mind like quills or border forts.

"Better to be dead and gone than housed in such corruption."

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of warping/transforming sound, though remember we're in imaginary space, we're talking about like an energy field changing.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>220</ID>
      <DefaultText>"No!" Anvor roars. "Never! To even touch your thoughts is corruption!"

And then the attack begins: all his will bent on your destruction, his mind scattered into barbed weapons soaring across the darkness. 

You are barely prepared for the sheer force of his hate.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>221</ID>
      <DefaultText>There is one who slips off the Mindlink's mask and staggers out of the Tabaht's tomb. You are not that one, but you are in it: not as some fraction or separate self, but as an indivisible part of a plural whole.

The newborn one looks with newly opened eyes at the sky, and limns it with newfound words, words exquisite in their precision: blues beyond blue. {[A] SOUND: Outdoors-y sounds: wind blowing, maybe birds chirping.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>222</ID>
      <DefaultText>Death has not dulled the Tabaht's weapons or his will. But the mind is more than a mere battlefield, and riddled and rotten as yours may be, it is not yet bereft of all its old gifts.

You confound Anvor's vanguard with a flurry of bright weavings, while stabbing your own lines of thought deep into the perfect geometry of his mind. In the end, that is all it takes: his thoughts destroy themselves, unraveling even as they seek to mend the breaches you have cut. Bit by bit, order turns to chaos, and the great light of Kalaghat Anvor becomes a mere shadow.

As he fades, you slip free of the Mindlink, and - moments later - of the Tabaht's tomb.

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of sound for minds battling: they're kind of shooting out energy at each other, or parts of thoughts. I'm at a loss to what sounds should be, but I think we do need some sound here. Maybe almost TRONish?}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>226</ID>
      <DefaultText>Then it's gone, again. Words and thoughts slip from you as you frantically struggle to hold on to what you can.

The worm's short gift has been squandered. They must be used carefully, sparingly.

With a shaking hand, you twist the tin shut and slip it back into your pocket.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>227</ID>
      <DefaultText>Then it's gone, again. Words and thoughts slip from you as you frantically struggle to hold on to what you can.

The worm's short gift has been squandered. They must be used carefully, sparingly.

With a shaking hand, you twist the tin shut and slip it back into your pocket.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>228</ID>
      <DefaultText>You flare your nostril and eagerly slip another worm inside, basking in the burst of pleasure it soon releases.

Though for a moment it seems as all existence has unfurled itself before you, you come down no wiser than you were, just sweaty from the brief ecstasy.

{[A] SOUND: Snorting a worm. Just a hard, drug-snorting sound.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
