    <Entry>
      <ID>231</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>232</ID>
      <DefaultText>Pain, and then the rush of sheer *knowing* that the worm's waste bestows. 

The symbols that seemed so indecipherable now dance through your mind, arraying themselves in patterns that could not be more obvious. That one is "soldier," and links to "warband," which chains into "army." Here is "battle," and here is "death" - over and over again.

The entire lexicon is yours, elegant in its precision and simplicity: a language bereft of natural disorder.

As your insight begins to slip away, you cling to the worm-won wisdom. It seems you held on tight enough, for the knowledge of Tabaht writing does not leave you when the inevitable stabbing pain fills your brain.

{[A] SOUND: Snorting a worm. Just a hard, drug-snorting sound.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>233</ID>
      <DefaultText>Your brain races with the speed brought on by the worm's piss, and through your thoughts run the Tabaht symbols, spinning, twisting, combining and dividing.

There is a meaning here, tangled amid the knotted glyphs. And your mind is unraveling it, surely...

But not fast enough. You thoughts become painfully, shamefully slow, and the puzzle you felt so close to breaking now seems impregnable.

Another worm. Just one more and your mind, honed like a sword, will slice through the skeins. You're sure of it, so sure of it you find yourself sniffing in anticipation, a predator on the scent.

{[A] SOUND: Snorting a worm. Just a hard, drug-snorting sound.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>234</ID>
      <DefaultText>Seconds after the grub goes up your nose, you feel a flash of joy and insight: *blood*. The cenotaph's basin wants blood.

In your mind's eye, you see it, filled almost to overflowing with its sacrifice, proof that the supplicant before Kalaghat Anvor is as war-eager as the Tabaht.

A moment later, it is a drizzle of your own blood that you are wiping away from your lip, your eyes aching and ears ringing from the loss of the worm's gift.

{[A] SOUND: Snorting a worm. Just a hard, drug-snorting sound.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>235</ID>
      <DefaultText>Another worm, and the cenotaph's puzzle crumbles before you. It seems so simple now, so obvious: a prayer woven within the story, a prayer of submission to the truth, the truth of war and blood and death.

You need but touch the glyphs and the way will open before you.

{[A] SOUND: Snorting a worm. Just a hard, drug-snorting sound.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>238</ID>
      <DefaultText>Your mind vastens under the worm's gnashing jaws, and you feel at one with this ancient tomb. Its plain walls reveal the work of ages past; you sense a pattern that long predates the Tabaht, the Memorialists, perhaps even the Ninth World.

As for the general and his crystal coffin, it speaks of the fear of time's defiling touch, a futile need to halt the world's turning. But the Tabaht are gone; nothing can be saved for long.

And so you sink back down from your high, your brain aching as if bruised.

{[A] SOUND: Snorting a worm. Just a hard, drug-snorting sound.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>239</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>240</ID>
      <DefaultText>Carved into the cenotaph's plinth is a wide, shallow bowl: perfectly smooth, perfectly ovoid. In its center is a small drain that runs into the monument. Around its rim is a geometric pattern, simple and composed of a single recurrent shape.

Your guide keeps back from the basin as you examine it, and shares no thoughts.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>241</ID>
      <DefaultText>Carved into the cenotaph's plinth is a wide, shallow bowl: perfectly smooth, perfectly ovoid. In its center is a small drain that runs into the monument. Around its rim is a geometric pattern, simple and composed of a single recurrent shape.

You recognize the symbol: "Blood." Of course. It could be nothing else.

Your guide keeps back from the basin as you examine it, and shares no thoughts.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>242</ID>
      <DefaultText>Anvor strives to bind you, to encircle and ensnare your mind for a final, fatal battle. With no hope of prevailing in such a match, you struggle to slip free...

But it's too late. His thoughts have slid inside you, wreaking havoc. You are forced to yield whole swaths of yourself to the invader in hopes of saving a small core of identity.

Something survives, and pulls off the Mindlink's reeking mask. It is you or, at least, a part of you. Neither the best nor the worst, merely that which fled fastest.

Maimed and dazed, you stagger forth from the tomb without a backward glance for the Tabaht corpse.

{[A] SOUND: Some kind of sound for minds battling: they're kind of shooting out energy at each other, or parts of thoughts. I'm at a loss to what sounds should be, but I think we do need some sound here. Maybe almost TRONish?}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>243</ID>
      <DefaultText>Blue. The portal behind you, the sky above you. It is a good, round word. You don't need or want a different one.

"Blue."

You roll the word around the vast cavern of your mind, enjoying the sound of it, enjoying the cool breeze on your skin, the fine monuments all about you.

The rest is gone, for good and for the better. {[A] SOUND: Outdoors-y sounds: wind blowing, maybe birds chirping.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>244</ID>
      <DefaultText>Anvor lets you slip free with but token resistance. The distance between you grows, the light of his pattern dims, and soon you are wrapped once more in a reeking leather mask. 

You pull the Mindlink off and, without a backward glance for the Tabaht corpse, stagger forth from the tomb.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>245</ID>
      <DefaultText>As the worm slithers into your brain and begins to feed, terrible convulsions wrack your body. No pleasure comes, no knowledge, just pain and trembling.

When it is done, the fluid that flows from your nose is not just blood: there is something else, something worse, in it as well.

{[A] SOUND: Snorting a worm. Just a hard, drug-snorting sound.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
