      <ID>249</ID>
      <DefaultText>As the worm slithers into your brain and begins to feed, terrible convulsions wrack your body. No pleasure comes, no knowledge, just pain and trembling.

When it is done, the fluid that flows from your nose is not just blood; there is something else, something worse in it as well.

{[A] SOUND: Snorting a worm. Just a hard, drug-snorting sound.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>250</ID>
      <DefaultText>This time, there is no pain - not even a little - but no pleasure either. Just a dullness, spreading outward and inward until there is nothing at all, just a vast flat expanse left of what were once the great heights of your mind.

And so you end.

{[A] SOUND: Snorting a worm. Just a hard, drug-snorting sound.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>251</ID>
      <DefaultText>The tomb, like your mind, holds nothing of value: only shades and scratchings of past glories. You leave it, and go back through the portal.

The sky above you is blue no longer. Just gray, with clouds so thick that they seem shapeless. The ground, like the world, is hard and old and as gray as the sky. Once, a visitant told you that it was an orb of blue and green. But that was long ago.

You drop the Mindlink and toss the crumpled note aside. Hand wrapped around the old, battered tin, you make your way between earth and sky, both gray, undifferentiated, indifferent.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
